@megfault: I've never really been big on sports. Though what has helped me a lot in the past is getting into early-hours running.

Either way, I was being a drama queen when I posted this thread :P. It's certainly not every night. Last night, for example, I was pretty okay.

@Sirenyc: I saw your video uploads. Pretty sweet. I'm downloading one now to try and help seed. But your upload is pretty slow (50kb/s?). My videos should all be properly seeded and watchable. I tested with the proxies and such (obviously connecting to myself, but you know :P).

It's not my site, so I can't help with bugs. As I said, I manually upload and sign/publish using the sidebar (with some tweaks to point to my user content.json).

@Edantes: Yea, if the site owner doesn't fix it up, I'll definitely look into making a fork and fixing it up. Webtorrent is pretty usable, so all it really needs is a nice front end for uploading/watching.

@Sirenyc: Haven't updated the index for a while. Sorry.

@Shellbound: Unfortunately most of the music I listen to isn't available for streaming on 'normal' services (spotify/google/tidal/etc). A few borderline illegal chinese services have some though :P.

@TeddyDD: MusicBrainz is one of those things that I like (it's a pretty solid system/software) but it's incredibly lacking in info and has no easy way of submitting my hundreds of tagged songs that aren't in the DB.

@Lain: It's already *technically* usable. It's pretty slow though, and lacks a lot of features I want to put in it. Right now it's a streamer/downloader for two popular chinese music sites: Xiami and Netease Music. Here's some screenshots:

[artist page](https://ipfs.pics/ipfs/QmWDSYSh2cEzUpnyLD4cPSWHcrVbNyg398JgbySeirb72x) - Grabs all the albums available, along with last.fm and musicbrainz data. Similar artists shown at the top there.

[search results](https://ipfs.pics/ipfs/QmaM7XN67F2kpzRaveyKTQ7hqGXPRySacoPGKoE5nsKGJ5) - Pretty straight forward. Shows the search results of whatever you're looking for.

[Album page+playing queued songs](https://ipfs.pics/ipfs/QmaicZJuVkMJgqQEZseVJY8uVp7kjKutqeUqMiQNrtSSF4) - Shows the tracks from both services, along with a variety of play/queue/download buttons. Has options to directly download a track or to download the whole album. The app automatically tags mp3s, and sorts into `artist/album/track.mp3`. Lyrics are obtained if available.

I keep feeling like I should shift it over to QT or something, rather than have it a webapp. Since managing the queue and such is getting clunky (I redirect to a new player page, with an iframe of the viewed page, and then manage URL state directly). I use flask at the moment, which is why I'm getting a bit of lag between pages switches (has to load content from two different chinese sites, then manage the data, maybe grab more content, etc.). The downloading isn't perfect yet (no downloads from netease), the merging is still a mess. And there's no easy way to manage your catalogue. No importing/uploads/whatever, as it's just a stream+download tool at the moment. I want to throw in a thing to log the data viewed into a database of some sort. Initially I thought maybe sending that to a hosted DB somewhere would work, but I want users to have access to it, and to not have the DB swarmed. I made a crawler for Xiami, but I haven't written stuff for logging just yet. I've mostly just worked on it off/on for the past while now. Xiami changed things up mid-dev, so I had to spend a lot of time fixing it. And netease seems to constantly shift their cdn stuff, which makes it keep breaking.

@Icf20: Looks like that's just ripping from youtube. Won't work for my purposes.

@Johnhamelink: I've seen beets, and it seems like it grabs from the usual sources :\\. I haven't seen the mopidy stuff though. I'll have to look into it.

@Elspru: Wasn't my choice. I was invited and accepted the invite. I'm just trying to sort out some stuff in my life, and the people helping me do that are using discord. I'm also a bit curious since I've seen it around.

In terms of libre software, I'm well aware discord doesn't follow suit. A lot of communication software I use unfortunately is not. And it can't be, unless I drag everyone I know into using stuff they'd almost certainly not be willing to use.

@Bbxxx: Fuck off. What the fuck is the point of posting that over and over? It's nonsensical english, isn't a link or advert for anything, and ultimately just acts as spam. Why do it? What motivation do you have?
